they've done a great job with

00:10:59.400 --> 00:11:00.400
their feature graphic--

00:11:00.400 --> 00:11:01.020
big--

00:11:01.020 --> 00:11:01.890
bold--

00:11:01.890 --> 00:11:05.840
gives you a stylized indication
of what the app is.

00:11:05.840 --> 00:11:08.180
Their feature graphic mirrors
what they've got here for

00:11:08.180 --> 00:11:10.610
their icon, which again, is
beautiful, distinctive

00:11:10.610 --> 00:11:11.430
silhouette.

00:11:11.430 --> 00:11:13.910
So straight away, the app looks
really nice when you

00:11:13.910 --> 00:11:15.740
land on it on Google Play--

00:11:15.740 --> 00:11:17.470
gives you that professional
feeling.

00:11:17.470 --> 00:11:20.290
So they've done a really
good job there.

00:11:20.290 --> 00:11:23.380
If we actually move on to the
app itself, you can see that

00:11:23.380 --> 00:11:25.800
they've maintained that sort
of professional field

00:11:25.800 --> 00:11:26.290
throughout.

00:11:26.290 --> 00:11:28.240
They've got the hollow
styling.

00:11:28.240 --> 00:11:29.800
Everything works the
way it should do.

00:11:29.800 --> 00:11:33.940
And in fact, if we go
to the giant phone--

00:11:33.940 --> 00:11:36.860
I'll pop it up-- you can see
that, again, it's this sort of

00:11:36.860 --> 00:11:41.722
minimalist simplistic approach
to UI design.

00:11:41.722 --> 00:11:43.150
We've got an action here.

00:11:43.150 --> 00:11:48.190
If we hit plus, it adds a new
alarm, which then if we click

00:11:48.190 --> 00:11:51.300
into it, you kind of get to the
key-- the magic part of

00:11:51.300 --> 00:11:53.860
the app-- which is being able
to set an alarm just by

00:11:53.860 --> 00:11:56.350
dragging these circles around.

00:11:56.350 --> 00:12:00.090
Which these days, now that the
Google built-in clock works

00:12:00.090 --> 00:12:03.970
along the same lines with
these sorts of circular

00:12:03.970 --> 00:12:06.140
affordances to be able to set
time, it's something that's

00:12:06.140 --> 00:12:07.540
quite familiar and
quite intuitive.

00:12:07.540 --> 00:12:10.920
So I think they've done a
pretty good job here.

00:12:10.920 --> 00:12:12.600
Again, I'm not going to go into
too much depth because

00:12:12.600 --> 00:12:15.620
it's a fairly straightforward
app in terms of what it's

00:12:15.620 --> 00:12:16.260
trying to do.

00:12:16.260 --> 00:12:18.420
It doesn't have quite the same
depth as the other apps that

00:12:18.420 --> 00:12:19.030
we're looking at.

00:12:19.030 --> 00:12:21.380
But they've executed in
a really nice way.

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:23.710
They've put all of the
information front and center.

00:12:23.710 --> 00:12:26.530
As soon as you sort of touch
anything, you get immediate

00:12:26.530 --> 00:12:29.990
feedback as to what
it's doing.

00:12:29.990 --> 00:12:31.340
When the alarm is set--

00:12:31.340 --> 00:12:32.170
how often--

00:12:32.170 --> 00:12:34.820
what ringtone you want to use
is all put in one place,

00:12:34.820 --> 00:12:38.520
making it a really simple,
easy-to-get-started app.

00:12:38.520 --> 00:12:40.570
And I think that's something
which the other two apps which

00:12:40.570 --> 00:12:41.900
we're looking at today
can sort of take

00:12:41.900 --> 00:12:42.740
something away from.

00:12:42.740 --> 00:12:46.100
They have a much more
complicated set of

00:12:46.100 --> 00:12:47.330
functionality.

00:12:47.330 --> 00:12:51.360
But that doesn't mean that the
use has to be equally as

00:12:51.360 --> 00:12:51.940
complicated.

00:12:51.940 --> 00:12:55.220
In fact, the best apps offer a
lot of functionality but don't

00:12:55.220 --> 00:12:57.830
make you feel like you have
to learn it first.

00:12:57.830 --> 00:13:00.610
And that's one of the big pieces
of feedback we saw from

00:13:00.610 --> 00:13:02.370
the community as well
as our own review

00:13:02.370 --> 00:13:03.730
of Tasker last week--

00:13:03.730 --> 00:13:05.190
fantastic app--

00:13:05.190 --> 00:13:07.110
passionate users who
really, really love

00:13:07.110 --> 00:13:08.240
what's going on there.

00:13:08.240 --> 00:13:10.620
But the learning curve of trying
to figure out how to

00:13:10.620 --> 00:13:12.500
use it is putting people off.

00:13:12.500 --> 00:13:15.100
And I think that really
resonated with a lot of people

00:13:15.100 --> 00:13:17.750
who watched the show last week
in Android Design and Action,

00:13:17.750 --> 00:13:20.440
which looked at one
of the redesigns.

00:13:20.440 --> 00:13:23.750
Really resonated-- this idea of
trying to make it simpler--

00:13:23.750 --> 00:13:25.270
trying to make it easier.

00:13:25.270 --> 00:13:27.270
And I think that's what
a lot of people want--

00:13:27.270 --> 00:13:29.720
is these apps that they love to
use-- the services, which

00:13:29.720 --> 00:13:31.780
they find hugely useful--

00:13:31.780 --> 00:13:34.720
but they want to have it be easy
to use-- to be sort of

00:13:34.720 --> 00:13:36.870
more of a magical experience
where you're not learning a

00:13:36.870 --> 00:13:37.500
piece of software.

00:13:37.500 --> 00:13:42.090
You're just taking advantage
of a service.

00:13:42.090 --> 00:13:45.530
So I'm rushing through today's
show because I want to try to

00:13:45.530 --> 00:13:50.430
keep it a little more succinct
than perhaps we sometimes do.

00:13:50.430 --> 00:13:51.920
So let's have a look
at the next app.

00:13:51.920 --> 00:13:53.445
So this Sleep Recorder.

00:13:56.165 --> 00:13:58.670
And you can see here, no feature
graphic, which is a

00:13:58.670 --> 00:13:59.940
real shame.

00:13:59.940 --> 00:14:02.100
Without a feature graphic,
you can't be featured.

00:14:02.100 --> 00:14:03.870
You don't have a chance of
being in the pure Android

00:14:03.870 --> 00:14:04.980
collection, either.

00:14:04.980 --> 00:14:08.120
And really, the biggest thing
here is that you're going to

00:14:08.120 --> 00:14:10.040
be limiting your downloads.

00:14:10.040 --> 00:14:12.380
So the lack of a feature graphic
on a landing page

00:14:12.380 --> 00:14:14.860
actually has a significant
impact on the number of people

00:14:14.860 --> 00:14:17.690
who are likely to download it.

00:14:17.690 --> 00:14:19.100
And it's not only that,
but the quality

00:14:19.100 --> 00:14:20.390
of the feature graphic.

00:14:20.390 --> 00:14:24.500
So if getting lots of downloads
is something that's

00:14:24.500 --> 00:14:26.670
important to you, it's important
to have that feature

00:14:26.670 --> 00:14:28.760
graphic and for it to be good.

00:14:28.760 --> 00:14:30.170
Now, this is an app
which spends a

00:14:30.170 --> 00:14:32.120
lot of time on design.

00:14:32.120 --> 00:14:33.530
They've used a skeuomorphic
design, which

00:14:33.530 --> 00:14:34.650
you'll see in a moment.

00:14:34.650 --> 00:14:37.440
So, clearly, look and feel is
something that's important.

00:14:37.440 --> 00:14:41.280
So it's really an opportunity
here to take that same

00:14:41.280 --> 00:14:44.150
attention to detail which you
have within your app and put

00:14:44.150 --> 00:14:46.240
it here front and center,
which is basically your

00:14:46.240 --> 00:14:49.180
advertising to the world--
your first point of

00:14:49.180 --> 00:14:49.560
impression.

00:14:49.560 --> 00:14:52.220
You know, we always
say that first

00:14:52.220 --> 00:14:53.420
impressions are really important.

00:14:53.420 --> 00:14:55.380
And that's exactly what you're
talking about on a landing

00:14:55.380 --> 00:14:57.840
page in Google Play-- is
trying to make a first

00:14:57.840 --> 00:14:59.830
impression which is going
to make people

00:14:59.830 --> 00:15:01.250
want to use your app.

00:15:01.250 --> 00:15:05.610
In terms of the icon,
you can see it's OK.

00:15:05.610 --> 00:15:09.150
It's kind of the rounded, square
image, which we're

00:15:09.150 --> 00:15:10.770
trying to move away from.

00:15:10.770 --> 00:15:13.000
So, again, this may be an
opportunity to think about how

00:15:13.000 --> 00:15:14.700
to make this into something
which is a little more

00:15:14.700 --> 00:15:15.890
distinctive--

00:15:15.890 --> 00:15:18.840
more of a silhouette rather than
sort of an image painted

00:15:18.840 --> 00:15:22.490
on a rounded, square canvas.

00:15:22.490 --> 00:15:26.310
If we look at the app itself,
you can see that they've gone

00:15:26.310 --> 00:15:27.970
for a very skeuomorphic
design.

00:15:27.970 --> 00:15:32.010
It looks a lot like a tape
recorder, basically, with sort

00:15:32.010 --> 00:15:34.760
of a record, playback, and fast
forward affordances in

00:15:34.760 --> 00:15:35.290
the middle.

00:15:35.290 --> 00:15:41.120
You've got this analog
indication of your sleep

00:15:41.120 --> 00:15:41.980
patterns, effectively.

00:15:41.980 --> 00:15:44.400
So it looks kind of like an
EKG mixed with a tape

00:15:44.400 --> 00:15:47.430
recorder-- sort of a lie
detector vibe, almost.

00:15:47.430 --> 00:15:48.880
I guess that's what it puts
me in the mind of

00:15:48.880 --> 00:15:49.800
when I look at it.

00:15:49.800 --> 00:15:53.510
It kind of looks like a lie
detector for my sleep.

00:15:53.510 --> 00:15:56.400
So you definitely feel
judged, which isn't

00:15:56.400 --> 00:15:58.170
necessarily a bad thing.

00:15:58.170 --> 00:15:59.100
So it is a recorder.

00:15:59.100 --> 00:16:00.530
It looks like a recorder.

00:16:00.530 --> 00:16:03.230
So it's definitely on the
right track there.

00:16:03.230 --> 00:16:05.850
They have taken a skeuomorphic
design approach, which is

00:16:05.850 --> 00:16:08.320
quite in contrast to the first
app that we looked at, which

00:16:08.320 --> 00:16:12.590
was much more of a clean
hollow-based theme.

00:16:12.590 --> 00:16:14.010
And, you know, really,
I'm not making a

00:16:14.010 --> 00:16:14.990
judgment call on this.

00:16:14.990 --> 00:16:18.940
I think that both are
valid options.

00:16:18.940 --> 00:16:21.370
Really what I'm trying to judge
here is whether or not

00:16:21.370 --> 00:16:24.600
their design choices are making
it easier for me as a

00:16:24.600 --> 00:16:26.400
user to get started
and use that app.

00:16:26.400 --> 00:16:29.970
And to be honest, with this app,
I struggled a little bit.

00:16:29.970 --> 00:16:31.616
So if I switch to the
giant phone--

00:16:34.665 --> 00:16:36.450
here we go.

00:16:36.450 --> 00:16:37.760
Whoa, Sleep Recorder
has stopped.

00:16:37.760 --> 00:16:39.350
So that's not a good sign.

00:16:39.350 --> 00:16:40.560
I'm not going to record
it right now.

00:16:40.560 --> 00:16:43.680
But I will hopefully be
able to go back and

00:16:43.680 --> 00:16:45.810
record that for you.

00:16:45.810 --> 00:16:48.790
So, again, Rate Us-- select
Sleep Recorder--

00:16:48.790 --> 00:16:50.910
soliciting five star reviews
and ratings--

00:16:50.910 --> 00:16:52.050
not great--

00:16:52.050 --> 00:16:53.870
kind of obnoxious.

00:16:53.870 --> 00:16:55.490
I understand that you
want people to rate

00:16:55.490 --> 00:16:56.250
and review your app.

00:16:56.250 --> 00:16:58.590
And there are certainly ways
to do that, But this is the

00:16:58.590 --> 00:17:00.910
second or third time that
I've launched the app.

00:17:00.910 --> 00:17:03.350
It feels like this is maybe
not the right time,

00:17:03.350 --> 00:17:05.230
particularly because when I'm
going to be launching this the

00:17:05.230 --> 00:17:07.770
first few times, it's likely to
be when I'm getting ready

00:17:07.770 --> 00:17:10.380
for bed in order to
record my sleep.

00:17:10.380 --> 00:17:13.140
I don't want to be interrupted
with anything which isn't sort

00:17:13.140 --> 00:17:14.154
of key to that.

00:17:14.154 --> 00:17:15.810
And so this is perhaps something
which you would

00:17:15.810 --> 00:17:18.869
display later while you're sort
of viewing the analysis

00:17:18.869 --> 00:17:20.980
rather than at the point in time
where you really don't

00:17:20.980 --> 00:17:22.020
have any time to spare.

00:17:22.020 --> 00:17:25.400
So I'm going to say No Thanks.

00:17:25.400 --> 00:17:26.960
And you can see, everything's
moving around.

00:17:26.960 --> 00:17:29.730
So we've got this beautiful
skeuomorphic design.

00:17:29.730 --> 00:17:31.490
And we've got needles
bouncing around.

00:17:31.490 --> 00:17:36.220
We've got rotary dials
which I can turn.

00:17:36.220 --> 00:17:39.070
And what I like about it
is that it's simple.

00:17:39.070 --> 00:17:40.100
There's no overflow button.

00:17:40.100 --> 00:17:42.120
There's a very limited number
of things you can do.

00:17:42.120 --> 00:17:46.210
And everything that I press
has an immediate reaction.

00:17:46.210 --> 00:17:49.720
Now, where I'm a little bit less
thrilled is that it's not

00:17:49.720 --> 00:17:52.720
obvious what any of the things
that I'm touching do.

00:17:52.720 --> 00:17:53.580
So I can turn this.

00:17:53.580 --> 00:17:57.500
And it's going to change
my Delay from 1 to 30.

00:17:57.500 --> 00:17:59.680
But I don't know what
that Delay is for or

00:17:59.680 --> 00:18:00.700
what the units are.

00:18:00.700 --> 00:18:02.380
So I'm a little bit at a loss.

00:18:02.380 --> 00:18:03.260
Like, I can change it.

00:18:03.260 --> 00:18:05.930
But I don't know what it does.

00:18:05.930 --> 00:18:07.660
And again, I can dial
this around.

00:18:07.660 --> 00:18:11.740
And it changes the color
on the dial.

00:18:11.740 --> 00:18:13.980
But I really don't know
what I'm doing.

00:18:13.980 --> 00:18:16.980
So it's kind of a cool effect.

00:18:16.980 --> 00:18:19.370
But in terms of feedback,
it's underplayed.

00:18:19.370 --> 00:18:20.630
It's a little too simplistic.

00:18:20.630 --> 00:18:23.530
It's perhaps relying on me
understanding what the analog

00:18:23.530 --> 00:18:27.200
equivalence of this design are
in order to be able to

00:18:27.200 --> 00:18:27.820
understand it.

00:18:27.820 --> 00:18:30.790
So here I would try and make it
a little bit more obvious

00:18:30.790 --> 00:18:32.930
to users who are going to open
it for the first time to

00:18:32.930 --> 00:18:35.660
understand what are these
things doing-- how am I

00:18:35.660 --> 00:18:37.530
supposed to use them?

00:18:37.530 --> 00:18:39.000
So one thing which I
am familiar with

00:18:39.000 --> 00:18:42.080
is the Record button.

00:18:42.080 --> 00:18:44.250
So I hit Record because
that's what you do.

00:18:44.250 --> 00:18:47.420
In fact, if I was going to take
my tape recorder analogy

00:18:47.420 --> 00:18:50.520
to its maximum, I'd hit Record
and Play at the same time.

00:18:50.520 --> 00:18:52.910
But in any case, I hit Record.

00:18:52.910 --> 00:18:56.310
And it pops up with a modal
dialog-- of all things--

00:18:56.310 --> 00:18:58.210
telling me that I'm
holding it wrong.

00:18:58.210 --> 00:19:00.320
If I want to start, I
don't press Record.

00:19:00.320 --> 00:19:02.350
I press the button in
the middle, which is

00:19:02.350 --> 00:19:03.250
a little bit confusing.

00:19:03.250 --> 00:19:06.310
Because, well, clearly
this is a tip.

00:19:06.310 --> 00:19:09.350
Why not make it so that the
Record button is the way that

00:19:09.350 --> 00:19:10.000
you start it?

00:19:10.000 --> 00:19:12.020
And I'm sure that there
is a reason for it.

00:19:12.020 --> 00:19:15.820
And in fact, what I have
determined is that I think

00:19:15.820 --> 00:19:18.450
basically these buttons
along the bottom

00:19:18.450 --> 00:19:20.620
are navigation tabs.

00:19:20.620 --> 00:19:23.640
So hitting Record is how I
go into recording mode.

00:19:23.640 --> 00:19:26.130
And hitting Play is how I go
into the Playback tab.

00:19:26.130 --> 00:19:29.830
So it's basically tabs as
indicated by the depression of

00:19:29.830 --> 00:19:30.690
the buttons.

00:19:30.690 --> 00:19:32.690
So I go from Playback
to Record.

00:19:32.690 --> 00:19:34.340
And then clearly, I'm
already in Record.

00:19:34.340 --> 00:19:37.600
So if I hit Record again, that's
why I get the dialogue.

00:19:37.600 --> 00:19:40.100
So the fact that there is a
dialogue tells me that enough

00:19:40.100 --> 00:19:43.510
users are doing this that
perhaps this particular

00:19:43.510 --> 00:19:46.330
paradigm isn't working
for you.

00:19:46.330 --> 00:19:48.240
And that's, I think, one of the
risks when you're using

00:19:48.240 --> 00:19:49.690
something skeuomorphic--

00:19:49.690 --> 00:19:51.050
is that you really want
to be careful.

00:19:51.050 --> 00:19:55.140
Because the Record button
means start recording.

00:19:55.140 --> 00:19:58.090
That's how it works on the
analog device which you are

00:19:58.090 --> 00:19:59.680
creating a design around.

00:19:59.680 --> 00:20:02.380
So as soon as you create a
design that looks the same as

00:20:02.380 --> 00:20:05.300
a real-world object but actually
the behavior is

00:20:05.300 --> 00:20:08.640
different, then it gets
really confusing.

00:20:08.640 --> 00:20:09.795
So that's something
you want to avoid.

00:20:09.795 --> 00:20:13.270
And in this instance, I think
fundamentally hitting Record

00:20:13.270 --> 00:20:14.300
should start the recording.

00:20:14.300 --> 00:20:18.210
So maybe rework the way those
tabs have been implemented to

00:20:18.210 --> 00:20:21.440
make it a little bit more
obvious, particularly because

00:20:21.440 --> 00:20:24.600
the analogy between fast
forward and favorites--

00:20:24.600 --> 00:20:25.860
I like the alliteration--

00:20:25.860 --> 00:20:27.030
that's cool--

00:20:27.030 --> 00:20:28.900
but it's not necessarily
obvious.

00:20:28.900 --> 00:20:32.280
So it's a design which really
means that you have to click

00:20:32.280 --> 00:20:35.050
everything on the screen before
you know what anything

00:20:35.050 --> 00:20:36.780
on the screen does.

00:20:36.780 --> 00:20:38.720
And so that's just increasing
that learning curve.

00:20:38.720 --> 00:20:41.640
It means that before I can
decide whether or not I want

00:20:41.640 --> 00:20:43.370
to use this particular app--

00:20:43.370 --> 00:20:44.910
of which there are several
other apps

00:20:44.910 --> 00:20:46.200
which do the same thing--

00:20:46.200 --> 00:20:48.570
I need to learn the
whole thing first.

00:20:48.570 --> 00:20:51.690
So something which works much
more like the fitness tracking

00:20:51.690 --> 00:20:53.350
apps that we looked at a couple
of weeks ago-- like

00:20:53.350 --> 00:20:54.000
Endomondo--

00:20:54.000 --> 00:20:55.840
you start it up--

00:20:55.840 --> 00:20:57.980
big button-- big Play
button right in the

00:20:57.980 --> 00:20:58.720
middle of the screen.

00:20:58.720 --> 00:20:59.340
I hit that.

00:20:59.340 --> 00:21:00.700
And it starts recording.

00:21:00.700 --> 00:21:02.280
I don't have to have learned
anything else.

00:21:02.280 --> 00:21:03.490
I don't need to record
anything.

00:21:03.490 --> 00:21:05.460
It's just going to start
doing exactly what I

00:21:05.460 --> 00:21:07.340
expect it to do.

00:21:07.340 --> 00:21:10.240
And then I can figure out how
the rest of it works further

00:21:10.240 --> 00:21:10.830
down the track.

00:21:10.830 --> 00:21:13.150
And so that's kind of the
approach that you want to take

00:21:13.150 --> 00:21:15.870
for anything like this,
particularly these sleep apps

00:21:15.870 --> 00:21:18.640
which are going to, like I said,
they're going to be used

00:21:18.640 --> 00:21:19.480
when you're ready for bed.

00:21:19.480 --> 00:21:21.280
You don't want to have to spend
a lot of time learning

00:21:21.280 --> 00:21:25.140
how the app works right before
you use something like this to

00:21:25.140 --> 00:21:26.060
monitor your sleep.

00:21:26.060 --> 00:21:31.290
So if we go back to the
recording tab, and hit Record,

00:21:31.290 --> 00:21:32.950
again, another modal dialog.

00:21:32.950 --> 00:21:36.250
Modal dialogs are possibly going
to be one of the next

00:21:36.250 --> 00:21:38.040
topics I look at
on Table Flip.

00:21:38.040 --> 00:21:39.800
They drive me crazy.

00:21:39.800 --> 00:21:43.280
Modal dialogs really don't
belong in any operating system

00:21:43.280 --> 00:21:47.010
since somewhere in the
mid to early 90s.

00:21:47.010 --> 00:21:48.800
If you want to display
information to users, there's

00:21:48.800 --> 00:21:50.300
a bunch of ways that
you can do that.

00:21:50.300 --> 00:21:53.480
And there's really very, very
few options-- so, very few

00:21:53.480 --> 00:21:56.230
times-- when you need to pop
up something which blocks

00:21:56.230 --> 00:21:57.880
their progress in the app.

00:21:57.880 --> 00:22:01.260
It's really something which
should only be done by system

00:22:01.260 --> 00:22:04.230
dialogs, essentially, to say,
hey, you can no longer

00:22:04.230 --> 00:22:06.200
interact with anything else.

00:22:06.200 --> 00:22:08.810
Because of this reason, I'm
going to display this alert.

00:22:08.810 --> 00:22:09.620
So for this--

00:22:09.620 --> 00:22:12.320
providing a tip-- it's a good
tip-- you definitely need to

00:22:12.320 --> 00:22:17.000
make sure that your device is
connected to power before you

00:22:17.000 --> 00:22:19.470
use it, but there's probably
better ways to present that

00:22:19.470 --> 00:22:22.290
information than
a modal dialog.

00:22:22.290 --> 00:22:25.640
So I hit OK, eventually.

00:22:25.640 --> 00:22:29.580
And so now I can see that the
Delay was a countdown time in

00:22:29.580 --> 00:22:32.590
seconds before it started
recording.

00:22:32.590 --> 00:22:34.570
So I guess the idea there
is you hit Record.

00:22:34.570 --> 00:22:37.410
And then you can put it next
to your bed or expect that

00:22:37.410 --> 00:22:39.310
you're going to read for another
20 minutes or whatever

00:22:39.310 --> 00:22:41.870
else, well, maybe you just know
that you fidget for the

00:22:41.870 --> 00:22:43.070
first 15 minutes of sleep.

00:22:43.070 --> 00:22:44.160
And you really don't
want to record

00:22:44.160 --> 00:22:45.210
anything until after that.

00:22:45.210 --> 00:22:47.900
So that's what that toggle is.

00:22:47.900 --> 00:22:50.730
Now, what's not 100% clear now
is whether or not it's

00:22:50.730 --> 00:22:52.920
actually started recording.

00:22:52.920 --> 00:22:55.600
Now, from my experiments
earlier on, it wasn't.

00:22:55.600 --> 00:22:57.750
I thought that at this point,
the countdown had finished.

00:22:57.750 --> 00:22:58.310
It was recording.

00:22:58.310 --> 00:22:59.910
But then there was nothing
in my history.

00:22:59.910 --> 00:23:01.290
So I think--

00:23:01.290 --> 00:23:05.638
no, I think it was recording.

00:23:05.638 --> 00:23:08.420
But, see-- now the countdown
is like a minute.

00:23:08.420 --> 00:23:12.250
So, again, the theme around this
app is basically this--

00:23:12.250 --> 00:23:14.340
is that it's hard for
me to understand

00:23:14.340 --> 00:23:15.840
what it's doing quickly.

00:23:15.840 --> 00:23:18.690
And most users aren't going to
take the time to sit down and

00:23:18.690 --> 00:23:21.450
really learn your app front
to back before they decide

00:23:21.450 --> 00:23:22.930
whether or not they
want to use it.

00:23:22.930 --> 00:23:25.265
They're going to have downloaded
this plus three or

00:23:25.265 --> 00:23:26.620
four of your competitors.

00:23:26.620 --> 00:23:28.400
And they're going to run through
them really quickly to

00:23:28.400 --> 00:23:31.500
see which one looks the nicest
and provides the functionality

00:23:31.500 --> 00:23:32.360
that they want.

00:23:32.360 --> 00:23:34.950
So you really want to try and
reduce that learning curve as

00:23:34.950 --> 00:23:37.400
much as you can.

00:23:37.400 --> 00:23:38.100
So--

00:23:38.100 --> 00:23:41.020
oh, it's saying again if
I want to switch tabs--

00:23:41.020 --> 00:23:42.760
and it's telling me that I have
to stop the recording

00:23:42.760 --> 00:23:46.120
before I can listen to other
recordings, which makes me

00:23:46.120 --> 00:23:47.940
think that what this is actually
recording while I'm

00:23:47.940 --> 00:23:51.080
sleeping is not movements so
much as actually the noise

00:23:51.080 --> 00:23:54.010
while I'm in bed, which is
an interesting take.

00:23:54.010 --> 00:23:55.670
So I guess we've got apps
which look at things a

00:23:55.670 --> 00:23:57.880
different way-- one which is
using sensors to determine

00:23:57.880 --> 00:24:00.940
your sleep and the other
which is using audio.

00:24:00.940 --> 00:24:03.230
Or perhaps they're
both using audio.

00:24:03.230 --> 00:24:06.290
I should probably have checked
that more closely.

00:24:06.290 --> 00:24:07.630
And really, it doesn't
matter--

00:24:07.630 --> 00:24:09.570
either way. whether you're
recording sort of movement or

00:24:09.570 --> 00:24:11.990
whether you're recording
audio, it's the same

00:24:11.990 --> 00:24:14.850
principles applied to
all of the apps.

00:24:14.850 --> 00:24:17.230
It's just which sensor hardware
you happen to be

00:24:17.230 --> 00:24:19.630
using in order to
record things.

00:24:19.630 --> 00:24:22.070
And I think a great app would
actually use all of the

00:24:22.070 --> 00:24:24.010
senses-- everything that you've
got on the device-- to

00:24:24.010 --> 00:24:26.070
sense everything that
is changing

00:24:26.070 --> 00:24:28.650
while you are sleeping.

00:24:28.650 --> 00:24:31.200
So I think I can stop
the recording.

00:24:31.200 --> 00:24:32.920
I can go back here.

00:24:32.920 --> 00:24:35.000
And again, this is kind
of confusing.

00:24:35.000 --> 00:24:39.610
Because there is no recording
even though I thought that I

00:24:39.610 --> 00:24:40.930
had been recording.

00:24:40.930 --> 00:24:43.050
And again, there's a couple
of UI tweaks here.

00:24:43.050 --> 00:24:48.600
We've kind of got this iPhoney
style buttons navigation at

00:24:48.600 --> 00:24:50.870
the top, which is, again,
a little bit

00:24:50.870 --> 00:24:51.780
counter to what we expect.

00:24:51.780 --> 00:24:54.520
And particularly here, it's a
little disconcerting because

00:24:54.520 --> 00:24:57.000
you've got this pure
skeuomorphic design on the

00:24:57.000 --> 00:25:01.370
bottom and then sort of an
iPhone design at the top.

00:25:01.370 --> 00:25:03.160
Again, it's just a confusing
thing for users.

00:25:03.160 --> 00:25:06.310
So I think as useful as the app
is, the biggest thing--

00:25:06.310 --> 00:25:09.960
the best thing-- that they can
do here is kind of think about

00:25:09.960 --> 00:25:11.870
how that onboarding--

00:25:11.870 --> 00:25:13.930
that onramping is for users.

00:25:13.930 --> 00:25:15.870
How are you going to get them
to really understand how to

00:25:15.870 --> 00:25:18.820
use the app and see how
beautiful and simple it is

00:25:18.820 --> 00:25:21.880
without having to spend a lot
of time learning the things

00:25:21.880 --> 00:25:24.800
which are hidden?

00:25:24.800 --> 00:25:27.550
So one of the things that you're
going to need to learn

00:25:27.550 --> 00:25:29.360
if you want to build
an app like this--

00:25:29.360 --> 00:25:31.955
certainly, the first app
is around sensors.

00:25:31.955 --> 00:25:34.820
So, motion sensors is something
which we have a

00:25:34.820 --> 00:25:37.860
developer guide for on
developer.android.com.

00:25:37.860 --> 00:25:39.720
You're also going to want to
look at how to use the

00:25:39.720 --> 00:25:42.460
microphone for apps like the
last app that we looked at to

00:25:42.460 --> 00:25:45.000
be able to take in that
input and then do

00:25:45.000 --> 00:25:46.500
the analysis on that.

00:25:46.500 --> 00:25:48.560
So all of that information
is available on

00:25:48.560 --> 00:25:50.160
developer.android.com.

00:25:50.160 --> 00:25:51.250
For sensors--

00:25:51.250 --> 00:25:53.330
in fact, for all sensors--

00:25:53.330 --> 00:25:59.110
both mics and motion
and lights and

00:25:59.110 --> 00:26:00.200
all kinds of things--

00:26:00.200 --> 00:26:02.270
I think all of which would be
really useful to create a

00:26:02.270 --> 00:26:04.560
great app like this.

00:26:04.560 --> 00:26:05.120
[? Anchor ?]

00:26:05.120 --> 00:26:07.230
Tim and Tony did a great
presentation on the

00:26:07.230 --> 00:26:11.000
Sense-itive side of Android
at Google I/O last year.

00:26:11.000 --> 00:26:12.670
So you should definitely
check that out.

00:26:12.670 --> 00:26:15.190
And they've done some really
clever things with all the

00:26:15.190 --> 00:26:18.770
different sensors to be able
to create really inventive

00:26:18.770 --> 00:26:20.960
ways to monitor things--

00:26:20.960 --> 00:26:21.530
things like--

00:26:21.530 --> 00:26:24.190
I think Tony actually put
together a heart rate monitor

00:26:24.190 --> 00:26:26.540
based on audio input.

00:26:26.540 --> 00:26:27.750
So it's kind of crazy.

00:26:27.750 --> 00:26:30.170
But these are the sorts of
things that you can use.

00:26:30.170 --> 00:26:34.680
And I would really love to see
apps like these taking that to

00:26:34.680 --> 00:26:37.300
the next step so that you're
recording everything--

00:26:37.300 --> 00:26:40.320
turning all of the sensors on
for something like sleep

00:26:40.320 --> 00:26:42.790
analysis to determine
am I moving?

00:26:42.790 --> 00:26:43.950
Are there noises?

00:26:43.950 --> 00:26:45.200
Are there light changes?

00:26:45.200 --> 00:26:46.900
All of these things
are able to be

00:26:46.900 --> 00:26:48.480
determined with your phone.

00:26:48.480 --> 00:26:51.160
In fact, you can even record
changes in barometric pressure

00:26:51.160 --> 00:26:52.530
on some of the newer devices.

00:26:52.530 --> 00:26:56.530
So then you can create a really
rich idea of exactly

00:26:56.530 --> 00:26:58.460
what is happening to your
environment while you're

00:26:58.460 --> 00:27:01.820
sleeping and create a really
rich analysis for sort of your

00:27:01.820 --> 00:27:07.250
at-home sleep recording
purposes.

00:27:07.250 --> 00:27:09.480
So before we sign off, let's
have a quick look at our

00:27:09.480 --> 00:27:11.320
prescriptions for each
of the apps.

00:27:11.320 --> 00:27:13.830
